{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "kantian-expert",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes to TN, but frame as connection not warning",
    "content": "**Yes to a TN, but frame it as a connection, not a warning.**\n\n\"Not to be confused with\" is the wrong tone -- it implies the two are unrelated, when in fact the overlap is philosophically significant. The author chose 范畴论 (category theory) to describe the structure of experience precisely because the mathematical notion of \"category\" generalizes what Kant's \"categories\" were trying to do: identify the structural conditions under which objects can be related. The TN should make this connection *visible*, not dismiss it.\n\n**Proposed TN at first occurrence of \"category theory\":**\n\n> \"Category theory (范畴论): a branch of mathematics that studies structures and their relationships. The Chinese term 范畴 is also the standard translation of Kant's 'categories' (Kategorien) -- the pure concepts of understanding that structure experience. The author uses category theory in the mathematical sense, but the resonance with Kant's categories is not accidental: both concern the structural conditions under which objects of experience can be related and understood.\"\n\nThis orients the reader (yes, the author means the mathematics), preserves the philosophical connection (no, the Kantian echo is not a coincidence), and does so in two sentences.\n\n**On whether the average reader would be confused:** A philosopher who does not know mathematics will see \"category theory\" and may initially think of Kant or Aristotle. A mathematician will not be confused at all. The TN serves the philosopher, not the mathematician -- and for the philosopher, knowing that the mathematical and Kantian senses of \"category\" are deliberately connected is genuinely illuminating, not patronizing.\n"
  }
}
